🌟Have you met our February cover star? It’s the incredible @LloydKnight!🤩

There are performances that stay seared in your brain. Knight’s interpretation of @MolissaFenley’s marathon solo “State of Darkness” in 2021 was one of them.

Over the course of 35 minutes, alone on the @TheJoyceTheater stage, Knight appeared to pass through various physical and mental states, from the serenity of an eagle in flight to alarm and physical frenzy, and, finally, to a kind of bliss, beyond time and space. And through it all, he maintained a precision, purity and beauty of movement that spoke of transcendence and absolute physical control. It was both an out-of-body and a profoundly in-the-body experience.

Read on Knight’s journey that led to his success and more at the link in our bio, and enjoy more exclusive behind the scenes clips on @DanceMagazine’s YouTube channel.✨

Story by @Marina.Harss

“I am a Black male, and that is something that is always with me," says @LloydKnight, our February cover star.✨

He says that @PeterLondonGDC “always pushed me to carry myself with pride and reminded me that I not only represent myself, but every Black person.”

Being one of the few Black men at Graham (and sometimes the only one) has been lonely at times. “Only because, you realize there haven’t been that many of us,” says Knight.

He says Black audience members have approached him after shows to tell him how much his presence means to them. He feels the honor of that, as well as a responsibility “to produce something really great.”🧡

Read more of Knight's cover story now at the link in our bio.

NEW@GRAHAM with Baye and Asa / March 14-15, 7 PM

Our March Studio Series presents a conversation and rehearsal showing with the dynamic choreographic team @bayeandasa about their Graham Company work-in-progress, CORTEGE 2023.

From the choreographers: “Drawing inspiration from Martha Graham’s CORTEGE OF EAGLES, Baye & Asa’s CORTEGE 2023 looks at Charon, the ferryman who shepherds souls to the underworld. In Graham’s work, Charon is a harbinger of Troy’s inevitable fall. In Baye & Asa’s creation, they ask: who is the ferryman for the fall of the American Empire?”

The #amazingdancers you see here are: @richardvillaverde @lloydknight @xin_ying_dance @__jamestony @anniesoud @lezandrea and @pagano_lorenzo791

On Jan 14 at Works & Process’s Underground Uptown Dance Festival, we also featured an in-process showing of the Works & Process commission, THE DRAMA by @lloydknight, @jackferver, and @jeremyjacob___. @marthagrahamdance Principal Dancer @lloydknight shared a first look at an intimate and personal solo inspired by the women in his life, his mother and Martha Graham. Knight’s work brought together research in the Martha Graham archive that was facilitated through a fellowship at the @nypl_lpa, @jeromerobbinsdancedivision and @worksandprocess LaunchPAD creative residencies with choreographer @jackferver and filmmaker @jeremyjacob___ at @bridgestreettheatre, @modernaccorddepot, and the @watermillcenter.
